						<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
							<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20250518100700/https://r-nimble.org/bayesian-nonparametric-models-in-nimble-part-1-density-estimation#comment-4379"><time datetime="2019-01-14T17:36:47-08:00">January 14, 2019 at 5:36 pm</time></a>

							<span class="support">
								<a rel="nofollow" class="comment-reply-link" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20250518100700/https://r-nimble.org/bayesian-nonparametric-models-in-nimble-part-1-density-estimation?replytocom=4379#respond" data-commentid="4379" data-postid="898" data-belowelement="comment-4379" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Chris Paciorek" aria-label="Reply to Chris Paciorek">Reply</a>															</span>
						</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

											</footer>

					<div class="comment-content entry-content"><p>Hi Andrew, thanks for the feedback. All our source code is at github.com/nimble-dev/nimble/packages/nimble,<br/>
with the BNP sampler code in particular at github.com/nimble-dev/nimble/packages/nimble/R/BNP_samplers.R<br/>
and the dCRP distribution at github.com/nimble-dev/nimble/packages/nimble/R/BNP_distributions.R.<br/>
We&#8217;d welcome another eye on it.</p>
<p>As far as how many components, if a user sets a truncation level, then if our MCMC sampling ever<br/>
tries to open too many components, we issue a warning and suggest that the user re-run the MCMC with<br/>
a lesser amount of truncation. But it does not error out.</p>
<p>We&#8217;re about to release our next version that should have big speed improvements in the sampling for CRP<br/>
models and will have additional improvements in the next release after that.</p>
</div>
				</article><!-- #comment-## -->

